00:00:30.698 --> 00:00:31.490
JULIAN BEINART: OK.

00:00:31.490 --> 00:00:41.010
Before we start, I've spoken
to a quite number of you

00:00:41.010 --> 00:00:42.090
about your papers.

00:00:47.550 --> 00:00:52.140
I'm a little surprised that
you have so much intelligence

00:00:52.140 --> 00:00:54.150
and so show little
in this class.

00:00:58.430 --> 00:01:02.510
It often fascinates me.

00:01:02.510 --> 00:01:04.910
I have various
theories to explain it,

00:01:04.910 --> 00:01:06.410
but they're not important.

00:01:10.360 --> 00:01:12.280
Let me start off
by asking you what

00:01:12.280 --> 00:01:14.830
you thought about the
story of Johannesburg.

00:01:19.210 --> 00:01:20.200
What struck you?

00:01:25.652 --> 00:01:26.152
[INAUDIBLE]

00:01:26.152 --> 00:01:30.790
AUDIENCE: What was the story
you told of the additions

00:01:30.790 --> 00:01:31.475
to the houses?

00:01:31.475 --> 00:01:32.350
JULIAN BEINART: Yeah.

00:01:32.350 --> 00:01:33.190
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:01:33.190 --> 00:01:38.440
I guess what struck me with
that is that, you know,

00:01:38.440 --> 00:01:41.770
on the one hand, there's
this constant appreciation

00:01:41.770 --> 00:01:48.670
of sort of individuals' efforts
and vernacular practices

00:01:48.670 --> 00:01:49.420
that come about.

00:01:49.420 --> 00:01:54.350
But then those so rarely
are institutionalized

00:01:54.350 --> 00:01:57.820
and are often restricted.

00:01:57.820 --> 00:02:01.200
So that was one
thing that struck me.

00:02:01.200 --> 00:02:03.200
JULIAN BEINART: Well,
these were not restricted,

00:02:03.200 --> 00:02:04.755
nor institutionalized.

00:02:04.755 --> 00:02:05.880
AUDIENCE: No, they weren't.

00:02:05.880 --> 00:02:06.930
Yeah.

00:02:06.930 --> 00:02:10.259
But I guess in
common in practice--

00:02:10.259 --> 00:02:14.920
but here in the States, if
you're zoning through so many

00:02:14.920 --> 00:02:17.530
things, you know that that is--

00:02:17.530 --> 00:02:20.380
even if that's
appreciated, there's

00:02:20.380 --> 00:02:23.080
never much thought into
how to encourage that.

00:02:27.700 --> 00:02:35.760
JULIAN BEINART: Well,
we presume that we

00:02:35.760 --> 00:02:41.650
passed the stage of needing
to externalize our importance.

00:02:44.210 --> 00:02:46.280
We haven't got the
motive for doing it.

00:02:46.280 --> 00:02:52.430
If we have, we do it in
tyranny and not externally,

00:02:52.430 --> 00:02:54.260
so the theory would go.

00:03:02.250 --> 00:03:07.860
We still believe,
probably, that we've

00:03:07.860 --> 00:03:12.090
reached a level of
civilization that

00:03:12.090 --> 00:03:17.725
doesn't require idiosyncratic
or highly personal expressions

00:03:17.725 --> 00:03:18.225
in public.

00:03:23.080 --> 00:03:26.770
We look at popular
art all over Africa

00:03:26.770 --> 00:03:32.080
and say that this is a culture
which has properties, but is

00:03:32.080 --> 00:03:35.590
still moving towards a climax.

00:03:35.590 --> 00:03:37.330
Its climax will be--

00:03:37.330 --> 00:03:42.235
much, though, the world of
Manhattan would be a climax.

00:03:44.840 --> 00:03:47.600
That's one theory.

00:03:47.600 --> 00:04:02.800
Another theory is that, in
people in the developing world,

00:04:02.800 --> 00:04:06.670
there are not many
resources available to them.

00:04:06.670 --> 00:04:11.920
So they have to develop
their own resources.

00:04:11.920 --> 00:04:14.770
Later in this class, when
I talk about Slum Dwellers

00:04:14.770 --> 00:04:18.579
International and the
latest configurations

00:04:18.579 --> 00:04:23.740
of self-help
organization, you will

00:04:23.740 --> 00:04:29.740
see that the strength of
people to organize themselves,

00:04:29.740 --> 00:04:32.920
a fundamental
premise of anarchism,

00:04:32.920 --> 00:04:38.080
is now rearing its head
as the only resource

00:04:38.080 --> 00:04:44.800
that poor people have against
enormous bureaucratic odds.

00:04:44.800 --> 00:04:48.155
So you can see it is a
very optimistic idea.

00:04:51.360 --> 00:04:56.370
The successes of SDI and its
equivalent on three continents

00:04:56.370 --> 00:04:59.640
so far would suggest
that there is something

00:04:59.640 --> 00:05:10.380
to be gained from not exploiting
but using or collectivizing

00:05:10.380 --> 00:05:15.000
the resources of
people in poverty

00:05:15.000 --> 00:05:18.410
towards organizing a
better situation for them.

00:05:24.180 --> 00:05:30.210
John Turner in Latin America,
John Aubrachen in Holland,

00:05:30.210 --> 00:05:34.410
were both at MIT at the
time I arrived here.

00:05:34.410 --> 00:05:40.770
And we shared stories about
what this kind of thing meant.

00:05:45.720 --> 00:05:47.310
Any other reactions?

00:05:47.310 --> 00:05:53.380
What about the imposition
of racial classification?

00:05:56.160 --> 00:06:00.990
Does the market impose
similar strictures

00:06:00.990 --> 00:06:04.680
on the location of people?

00:06:04.680 --> 00:06:08.630
Was the South African
situation just another version,

00:06:08.630 --> 00:06:15.450
an extreme version, of what
the market does anyway?

00:06:15.450 --> 00:06:20.280
Remember Western Native Township
was located next to a dump.

00:06:20.280 --> 00:06:29.010
Soweto was located next
to very obnoxious land.

00:06:29.010 --> 00:06:31.920
I think sewage farms and so on.

00:06:34.830 --> 00:06:36.810
Isn't this what happens?

00:06:36.810 --> 00:06:39.300
Look, I'm looking at
extreme situations

00:06:39.300 --> 00:06:42.990
in order to do the difficult
thing of generalizing back

00:06:42.990 --> 00:06:44.850
to normality.

00:06:44.850 --> 00:06:46.755
I'm not taking Boston as a case.

00:06:50.840 --> 00:06:52.570
I'm not taking
[INAUDIBLE]---- well,

00:06:52.570 --> 00:06:54.430
I am taking
[INAUDIBLE] as a case.

00:06:58.780 --> 00:07:05.920
And what I'm trying to do is
what perhaps medical professors

00:07:05.920 --> 00:07:10.150
do when looking at
teaching about cancer.

00:07:10.150 --> 00:07:13.150
They look at the worst
case, the most extreme case

00:07:13.150 --> 00:07:16.600
of the disease, in
order to make the point

00:07:16.600 --> 00:07:19.450
as clearly as possible.

00:07:19.450 --> 00:07:25.190
I think there is a sense
in my using Johannesburg.

00:07:25.190 --> 00:07:28.960
South Africa would not have
been marginalized had it not put

00:07:28.960 --> 00:07:31.090
race classification into law.

00:07:34.240 --> 00:07:40.300
Nobody boycotted America in
the early years of the century,

00:07:40.300 --> 00:07:46.510
of the last century, by
having local conditions

00:07:46.510 --> 00:07:47.650
against Black people.

00:07:52.120 --> 00:07:55.030
Many of the countries who
voted against South Africa

00:07:55.030 --> 00:07:57.130
in the United
Nations were imposing

00:07:57.130 --> 00:08:04.810
harsher, but not legalized
national constitutional devices

00:08:04.810 --> 00:08:08.860
in favor of the separation
of white and Black

00:08:08.860 --> 00:08:10.030
or poor and rich.

00:08:14.620 --> 00:08:16.520
Does that make any sense?

00:08:23.600 --> 00:08:29.625
What about rejoicing on the
products of poor people?

00:08:32.330 --> 00:08:36.980
When poor people struggle
to maintain some decent life

00:08:36.980 --> 00:08:39.215
beyond poverty, we rejoice.

00:08:43.610 --> 00:08:46.000
AUDIENCE: Are you saying
this from a schadenfreude

00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:47.658
perspective or from a--

00:08:47.658 --> 00:08:48.700
JULIAN BEINART: Probably.

00:08:48.700 --> 00:08:51.065
AUDIENCE: --or from a-- we
just enjoy what they produce

00:08:51.065 --> 00:08:51.690
and enjoy the--

00:08:54.500 --> 00:08:59.300
JULIAN BEINART: It's difficult.
I'm judging from the response

00:08:59.300 --> 00:09:02.780
that I have had in many
parts of the world when

00:09:02.780 --> 00:09:07.940
showing this material over
a number of years on the BBC

00:09:07.940 --> 00:09:09.700
and all over the place.

00:09:13.980 --> 00:09:16.700
It was on the cover of three
architectural magazines

00:09:16.700 --> 00:09:21.810
in the same month in 1966.

00:09:21.810 --> 00:09:26.190
It's a long time ago,
but there was something.

00:09:26.190 --> 00:09:28.200
Whenever I went
somewhere, architects

00:09:28.200 --> 00:09:34.470
were saying, gosh, if only we,
our clients in social housing,

00:09:34.470 --> 00:09:37.920
had that capacity to
individuate the buildings.

00:09:43.310 --> 00:09:45.590
And John Aubrachen,
amongst others,

00:09:45.590 --> 00:09:49.130
made big theory in his
book supports and others

00:09:49.130 --> 00:09:56.650
of the process of indwelling
as being something

00:09:56.650 --> 00:09:59.410
that we should cultivate.

00:09:59.410 --> 00:10:03.730
Architects should only build
if it required support systems

00:10:03.730 --> 00:10:06.716
to let people finish
the work themselves.

00:10:10.390 --> 00:10:13.360
In the three cases
which I want to deal

00:10:13.360 --> 00:10:17.770
with very briefly
this afternoon,

00:10:17.770 --> 00:10:20.440
we find a number of
different things operating.

00:10:23.170 --> 00:10:29.260
The Mexican-American
border is 1,952 miles long.

00:10:29.260 --> 00:10:33.190
It's the longest border in
the world, the least defended

00:10:33.190 --> 00:10:34.570
and the most patrolled.

00:10:40.480 --> 00:10:43.690
It's the largest tourist
crossing in anywhere

00:10:43.690 --> 00:10:44.350
in the world.

00:10:49.240 --> 00:10:54.930
Yet it has 11 binational
cities along the border.

00:10:57.580 --> 00:11:05.560
They vary from Tijuana,
San Ysidro, San Diego,

00:11:05.560 --> 00:11:17.020
to Ciudad Juarez, and El Paso
to the wonderful mix Californian

00:11:17.020 --> 00:11:19.960
pair of Calexico
and Mexicali, which

00:11:19.960 --> 00:11:25.090
is a wonderful anagram
of the linguistics.

00:11:25.090 --> 00:11:31.570
Nogales, Nogales, Brownsville,
Matamoros on the Gulf.

00:11:31.570 --> 00:11:33.220
How should we regard the cities?

00:11:36.980 --> 00:11:39.830
I will show evidence to
show that they operate

00:11:39.830 --> 00:11:46.340
in some ways as unified
metropolitan areas, which

00:11:46.340 --> 00:11:52.370
would mean that this
subregion along the border

00:11:52.370 --> 00:11:55.910
could be justified as
a separate identity

00:11:55.910 --> 00:11:59.632
from either Mexico
and the United States.

00:11:59.632 --> 00:12:01.590
AUDIENCE: When I was in
the Mexican government,

00:12:01.590 --> 00:12:06.080
we used to study
the thesis a lot.

00:12:06.080 --> 00:12:09.390
And I remember talking
to people especially,

00:12:09.390 --> 00:12:13.010
in Tijuana San Diego, on
both sides of the border.

00:12:13.010 --> 00:12:16.610
They actually refer to the
city as the Metropolitan area

00:12:16.610 --> 00:12:18.530
Tijuana San Diego.

00:12:18.530 --> 00:12:22.490
And their perspective
on the crossing point,

00:12:22.490 --> 00:12:24.770
on the checkpoint
right at the border,

00:12:24.770 --> 00:12:28.340
is [INAUDIBLE] sort of
a permanent nuisance

00:12:28.340 --> 00:12:30.600
that they have to deal
with in their daily lives.

00:12:30.600 --> 00:12:36.015
Because people work and
commute daily to the city.

00:12:36.015 --> 00:12:36.890
JULIAN BEINART: Yeah.

00:12:39.920 --> 00:12:46.970
In all of these cases, there's
an important friction system

00:12:46.970 --> 00:12:48.380
operating.

00:12:48.380 --> 00:12:52.520
In this case, it's between white
people and non-white people,

00:12:52.520 --> 00:12:57.870
between people of Hispanic
heritage or an Indian heritage

00:12:57.870 --> 00:12:58.370
and--

00:13:03.870 --> 00:13:08.120
El Paso is amongst the poorest
parts of the United States.

00:13:08.120 --> 00:13:10.820
When I was on the border in--

00:13:13.430 --> 00:13:16.430
after Jimmy Carter
became president,

00:13:16.430 --> 00:13:18.920
I attended some of
the meetings which

00:13:18.920 --> 00:13:21.440
he and the Mexican
president set up

00:13:21.440 --> 00:13:24.350
on some of these border towns.

00:13:32.810 --> 00:13:37.520
Octavio Paz says that
Mexico, crossing the border,

00:13:37.520 --> 00:13:40.430
is one of the ways
in which Americans

00:13:40.430 --> 00:13:42.140
satisfy their obsessions.

00:13:46.350 --> 00:13:48.630
It refers to a larger idea.

00:13:48.630 --> 00:13:53.940
And that is the uses of
slums in metropolitan areas.

00:13:53.940 --> 00:13:57.180
In Sherlock Holmes,
the Prince Royal

00:13:57.180 --> 00:14:03.480
goes off to smoke or take
cocaine in the East Indian

00:14:03.480 --> 00:14:05.190
London.

00:14:05.190 --> 00:14:09.510
Sherlock Holmes himself
smokes something or other.

00:14:13.430 --> 00:14:15.770
The poorest part
of the population

00:14:15.770 --> 00:14:21.380
provides a setting for the
doing of semi-legal or illegal

00:14:21.380 --> 00:14:24.300
things, prostitution and so on.

00:14:24.300 --> 00:14:30.530
So if you enlarge that and
you see Tijuana and San

00:14:30.530 --> 00:14:34.460
Diego as a pair--

00:14:34.460 --> 00:14:40.100
in Kevin Lynch and [INAUDIBLE]
study of San Diego of Tijuana,

00:14:40.100 --> 00:14:42.590
which is in the
reading, it's one

00:14:42.590 --> 00:14:46.790
of the best pieces of small
scale difficult planning

00:14:46.790 --> 00:14:48.860
that I know.

00:14:48.860 --> 00:14:51.020
It's in the reading
for today's class.

00:14:56.460 --> 00:15:06.570
You get a sense of
this idea that--

00:15:06.570 --> 00:15:09.960
remember Steve McQueen?

00:15:09.960 --> 00:15:12.860
He's a famous
American male actor

00:15:12.860 --> 00:15:17.670
who got cancer and a lot of
publicity associated with him

00:15:17.670 --> 00:15:21.460
crossing the border to the
South to get the illegal drug

00:15:21.460 --> 00:15:25.740
laetrile, which is not
available in the United States.

00:15:25.740 --> 00:15:28.410
Of course, it didn't
kill his cancer.

00:15:28.410 --> 00:15:31.110
But the phenomenon
of there being

00:15:31.110 --> 00:15:34.530
a haven, a special
environment which

00:15:34.530 --> 00:15:38.940
provides the majority
or the superior,

00:15:38.940 --> 00:15:45.000
quote "superior" class,
with satisfactions

00:15:45.000 --> 00:15:49.420
which are elicit in
their own surroundings.

00:15:49.420 --> 00:15:52.130
AUDIENCE: The phenomenon
still stands today.

00:15:52.130 --> 00:15:55.557
Close to the border, there's
a huge amount of pharmacies.

00:15:55.557 --> 00:15:56.390
JULIAN BEINART: Yes.

00:15:56.390 --> 00:15:59.320
AUDIENCE: They sell medicines
that here, in the States,

00:15:59.320 --> 00:16:03.440
would be either restricted by a
prescription or not available.

00:16:03.440 --> 00:16:05.970
JULIAN BEINART: Well,
two reactions to that--

00:16:05.970 --> 00:16:11.540
the border between East
Germany and West Germany--

00:16:11.540 --> 00:16:18.560
also, borders attract a
kind of marginal population.

00:16:18.560 --> 00:16:22.520
There's a wonderful little
book in your reading called

00:16:22.520 --> 00:16:26.840
On The Border by Tom Miller--

00:16:26.840 --> 00:16:29.330
he's a New York
Times journalist--

00:16:29.330 --> 00:16:32.630
which records a trip from
Brownsville, Matamoros

00:16:32.630 --> 00:16:37.130
all the way to Tijuana and the
extraordinary things he find.

00:16:37.130 --> 00:16:40.460
He finds a town
which specializes

00:16:40.460 --> 00:16:46.880
in the smuggling of peacocks to
Chicago in the back of trucks.

00:16:46.880 --> 00:16:52.280
He finds the most powerful AM
station in the United States,

00:16:52.280 --> 00:16:55.850
a right-wing propaganda
radio station

00:16:55.850 --> 00:16:58.430
which the government of
China asked the United

00:16:58.430 --> 00:17:01.850
States to intervene with.

00:17:01.850 --> 00:17:06.710
So there's a kind
of erotic condition

00:17:06.710 --> 00:17:09.035
where you bring two
notions together.

00:17:13.260 --> 00:17:18.180
I don't know what the
theory behind that is.

00:17:18.180 --> 00:17:22.510
But it seems to be the
case that the behavior

00:17:22.510 --> 00:17:27.540
of a lot of activities
on this border

00:17:27.540 --> 00:17:30.167
are different from the internet.

00:17:30.167 --> 00:17:32.250
AUDIENCE: There is a book
by the editor of Foreign

00:17:32.250 --> 00:17:34.470
Revue [INAUDIBLE] Moises Naim.

00:17:34.470 --> 00:17:38.460
The book is called
Illicit, where

00:17:38.460 --> 00:17:43.620
he studies borders in
details as constructs that,

00:17:43.620 --> 00:17:46.650
because of their--

00:17:46.650 --> 00:17:50.190
artificial blockage of
goods, services, and people's

00:17:50.190 --> 00:17:54.540
daily activities, it brings
out a particular kind

00:17:54.540 --> 00:17:57.960
of inhabitant of these places.

00:17:57.960 --> 00:18:01.440
JULIAN BEINART: This
Mexican-American border

00:18:01.440 --> 00:18:04.230
serves a number of
other functions.

00:18:04.230 --> 00:18:08.910
It serves as the major
avenue of illegal immigration

00:18:08.910 --> 00:18:10.950
into the United States.

00:18:10.950 --> 00:18:13.470
I don't know if there's
illegal immigration south

00:18:13.470 --> 00:18:17.820
from the United States
into Mexico, but--

00:18:17.820 --> 00:18:20.070
AUDIENCE: There are a lot
of people that go to Mexico.

00:18:20.070 --> 00:18:22.020
We don't ask
Americans for a visa.

00:18:22.020 --> 00:18:25.920
They enter, and then they
stay in Mexico and live there.

00:18:25.920 --> 00:18:26.970
JULIAN BEINART: Yeah.

00:18:26.970 --> 00:18:29.850
There are, according
to government sources,

00:18:29.850 --> 00:18:34.230
12 million illegal immigrants
in the United States.

00:18:34.230 --> 00:18:38.580
The census or one of
the government agencies

00:18:38.580 --> 00:18:45.060
claims it only arrests
one out of four people who

00:18:45.060 --> 00:18:48.580
try to take their bodies.

00:18:48.580 --> 00:18:52.665
56% of illegal immigrants
in this country are Mexican.

00:18:55.210 --> 00:19:01.030
So this border serves as
an avenue for the movement

00:19:01.030 --> 00:19:03.880
of people from--

00:19:03.880 --> 00:19:05.230
what would you call Mexico?

00:19:07.840 --> 00:19:09.550
What would you call
the United States?

00:19:09.550 --> 00:19:14.890
The United States offers more,
presumably more, opportunities

00:19:14.890 --> 00:19:16.840
for increasing wealth.

00:19:19.990 --> 00:19:23.770
There are many stories
that are humorous

00:19:23.770 --> 00:19:27.790
surrounding that there are
people who live in Mexico

00:19:27.790 --> 00:19:31.460
and work in the United
States illegally every day.

00:19:31.460 --> 00:19:33.730
One of the stories
in our meeting

00:19:33.730 --> 00:19:38.620
was told by a young man who
dresses up in jogging clothes

00:19:38.620 --> 00:19:42.310
like an American, crosses
the border every morning at 5

00:19:42.310 --> 00:19:47.440
o'clock, starts jogging
on the American side

00:19:47.440 --> 00:19:55.610
and works as a gardener,
returns home at night.

00:19:55.610 --> 00:19:57.550
These are funny stories.

00:19:57.550 --> 00:19:59.700
Immigration into
the United States

00:19:59.700 --> 00:20:06.280
is politically and spatially
still very unresolved.

00:20:06.280 --> 00:20:09.890
America was built by immigrants.

00:20:09.890 --> 00:20:12.700
I'm an immigrant.

00:20:12.700 --> 00:20:16.105
And I've taught
here for 34 years.

00:20:16.105 --> 00:20:20.730
It shows how poor the
local population is.

00:20:20.730 --> 00:20:22.230
[LAUGHTER]

00:20:29.270 --> 00:20:31.040
